snippet.textDisplay: This is a good example of "have keyboard, drums and guitars...will make noise". Why is this fusion? Let me guess. Take a classic, preferably sanskrit or tamil sloka, whose melodic structure is inherently beautiful and impeccable, and then, cut and paste into it another sound which is totally unrelated. You don't really need human beings to do this because this is not a humanistic experience, not born of a theory of the mind or behavior. It is a random act of conjoining irrelevant pieces. A bit-rate programmer can write code to grab two audio files, and smash them together, and call it fusion. It is fusion in a literal sense, not fusion in an aesthetic sense. For that you need the calibre of someone like Sri Ilayaraja. Go check out some of the outstanding pieces he has created (of all rAgAs, he picked chala nattai and delivered a mind-blowing result that is internally coherent).
